item.content:encoded:
So there are a few parallax libraries out there that do a wonderful job of adding the "trendy" effect to your website, and most of them pretty small in size too. But there is a very simple, little known, CSS property that can cause pretty much the same effect on a background image that most parallaxers (yes, I just made up a word for that... don't judge me!) use these libraries for.

<!--more-->

It's called: <code>background-attachment</code>

So simple this is, that adding just <b>one</b> line of code to your CSS can create a wonderful looking (albeit, basic) parallax effect on any page:
<div class="well"><code>background-attachment: fixed;</code></div>
<div class="example iframe-example"><iframe id="iframe" src="http://sebastianbailey.co.uk/blog/2015/css-parallax-example.html" width="300" height="150" frameborder="0"></iframe></div>
The main thing to note with this however, is that you have to set the<code>background-size</code> to <code>cover</code>, and the "cover" effect is on the overall container. So you will notice that with the header, if the content is above the fold, then you will not see some of the header image. My suggestion to this would be to then make the 'header' div a 100% height, which is the common and stylish norm nowadays anyway.
<h2>So here is the code you need for the above example:</h2>
<h3>HTML:</h3>
<div class="well">
<pre><code>&lt;div class='example-header'&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class='content'&gt;
	&lt;h2&gt;This is some content!&lt;/h2&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Lorem ipsum&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Lorem ipsum&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class='mid-strip'&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class='content'&gt;
	&lt;h2&gt;This is some more content...&lt;/h2&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Lorem ipsum&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
</div>
<h3>CSS:</h3>
<div class="well">
<pre><code>.header {
	height: 300px;
	width: 100%;
	background: url('**IMAGE URL**');
	background-size: cover;
	background-attachment: fixed;
	background-position: center;
}
.content {
	padding: 10px;
}
.mid-strip {
	height: 200px;
	width: 100%;
	background: url('**IMAGE URL**');
	background-size: cover;
	background-attachment: fixed;
	background-position: center;
}</code></pre>
</div>
Et voila! Enjoy your simple CSS parallax effect! :)
